The '''Cherokee calendar''' is defined by the seasonal round of ceremonies practiced by the [[Cherokee people]].  Although a modern calendar year comprises 12 months, there are actually 13 cycles or phases of the moon in the Cherokee calendar.{{citation needed|date=December 2012}}  The seasonal round of ceremonies is considered a necessary spiritual element for social cohesion and encourage gatherings among the [[Cherokee clans]] and [[Cherokee]] society.

== Cherokee names for Julian calendar months ==
* January: ''Unolvtana'' or ''Unâlatŭni'',<ref name=feeling>Feeling 234</ref> meaning "windblown",<ref name=lsd>Dubin 193</ref> {{sfn|Mooney|1894}}
* February: ''Kagaʔli'' or ''Gŭgăli'',<ref name=feeling/> Bone Moon,{{citation needed|date=December 2012}} "month when the stars and moon are fixed in the heavens"<ref name=lsd/>
* March: ''Anvhyi'', referring to strawberries (anŭ),{{sfn|Mooney|1894}}
* April: ''Kawohni'', or ''Kùwáni''<ref name=feeling/> meaning "duck" as in "when the ducks return", "ducks swim in ponds month",<ref name=lsd/> {{sfn|Mooney|1894}}
* May: ''Anisgvti'', ''Ansgvti'',<ref name=feeling/> "planting moon",{{citation needed|date=December 2012}} month of strawberries<ref name=lsd/> or making pottery (ŭntĭ){{sfn|Mooney|1894}}
* June: ''Dehaluyi'',<ref name=feeling/> "planting corn",{{citation needed|date=December 2012}} blackberry month<ref name=lsd/>
* July: ''Kuyegwona'',<ref name=feeling/> "ripe corn moon", {{citation needed|date=December 2012}} huckleberry month<ref name=lsd/>
* August: ''Gaʔloni'',<ref name=feeling/> fruit moon,{{citation needed|date=December 2012}} wild grapes month, [[Green Corn ceremony]]<ref name=lsd/> refers to drying up of the streams. {{sfn|Mooney|1894}}
* September: ''Dulisdi'',<ref name=feeling/> nut moon,{{citation needed|date=December 2012}} translation unknown, Bounding Bush Feast<ref name=lsd/>
* October: ''Dunihidi'', ''Duninhdi'',<ref name=feeling/> harvestime month, Great New Moon Ceremony<ref name=lsd/>
* November: ''Nvdadequa'', ''Nvdadeqwa,''<ref name=feeling/> big moon month,<ref name=lsd/> {{sfn|Mooney|1894}}
* December: ''Vsdgiyi'', ''Vskihyi'',<ref name=feeling/> snow moon,{{citation needed|date=December 2012}} translation unknown<ref name=lsd/>

==Seasons==
* Spring, ''Gagéyl'', "near the summer"
* Summer, ''Gagi''
* Early Autumn, ''Gúyû''
* Late Autumn, Ulăgăhûstû (refers to falling of the leaves)
* Winter, Gâlû  {{sfn|Mooney|1894}}

