Rev. '''Irving Clinton Tomlinson''' (March 22, 1860 – October 1, 1944) was an American Universalist minister who converted to [[Christian Science]],<ref>Peel, Robert. ''The Years of Authority''. Holt, Rinehart and Winston (1977), p. 109</ref> becoming a [[Christian Science practitioner|practitioner]] and teacher. For a time, he lived as one of the workers in the household of church founder, [[Mary Baker Eddy]], later writing a book about his experiences, called, ''Mary Baker Eddy: Twelve Years with Mary Baker Eddy''.
== Life == Born Irving Clinton Tomlinson, in [[Perry, New York]], he was the son of Dewitt Clinton, a minister and Emmeline C. Eaton Tomlinson.<ref>[http://records.ancestry.com/Irving_C_Thomlinson_records.ashx?pid=31961144 Irving C. Thomlinson] Ancestry.com. Retrieved June 29, 2013</ref> The family moved to [[Akron]], Ohio, where his father was involved with raising funds to build a new [[Universalism|Universalist]] educational institution, and where Tomlinson later went to [[University-preparatory school|preparatory school]] and college.<ref>Spanton, A. I., editor. [https://archive.org/stream/fiftyyearsofbuch00buchrich#page/14/mode/2up/search/Tomlinson ''Fifty Years of Buchtel: 1870-1920''] Buchtel College Alumni Association (1922), p. 15. Retrieved June 29, 2013</ref><ref>[https://archive.org/stream/fiftyyearsofbuch00buchrich#page/144/mode/2up/search/Tomlinson ''Fifty Years of Buchtel'', p. 145] Retrieved June 29, 2013</ref> He was the class president of a senior class of seven students,<ref name="abj">Price, Mark J. [http://www.ohio.com/lifestyle/history/local-history-university-of-akron-landmark-is-a-rock-of-ages-1.240604 "Local history: University of Akron landmark is a rock of ages"] ''Akron Beacon Journal'' Online. (October 16, 2011). Retrieved June 28, 2013</ref> and business manager of ''The Argo'', the first student publication at [[Buchtel College]].<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/fiftyyearsofbuch00buchrich#page/300/mode/2up/search/Tomlinson ''Fifty Years of Buchtel'', p. 301] Retrieved June 29, 2013</ref> He was also a member of [[Phi Delta Theta]], a fraternity.<ref name="scroll">[http://thescroll.imirus.com/Mpowered/book/v1944/i1/p158 "Chapter Grand"] ''The Scroll of Phi Delta Theta'', Vol. 69, No. 2 (November 1944), pp. 159-160. Retrieved June 30, 2013</ref>
While a senior, he and his classmates decided to surpass an effort made by the previous year's graduating class, which had been to place a two-ton boulder on the campus, a lasting reminder of them. Tomlinson and his classmates searched the vicinity and located a [[syenite]] boulder on a farm belonging to the industrialist son of [[Simon Perkins|Akron's founder]], Colonel Simon Perkins.<ref name="abj" /> Tomlinson was sent to purchase the "pebble", as they called it,<ref name="50-369">[https://archive.org/stream/fiftyyearsofbuch00buchrich#page/368/mode/2up/search/Tomlinson ''Fifty Years of Buchtel'', pp. 369-370] Retrieved July 2, 2013</ref> which measured 7 feet tall, 5 feet wide and 3.5 feet across (2.1×1.5×1.1m) and 90 cubic feet (23 [[cubic meter|m<sup>3</sup>]]).<ref name="abj" /> The owner didn't want to sell and didn't think Tomlinson and his friends would be able to move it, saying "six yoke of oxen weren't able to budge it." Tomlinson replied, "But, Colonel, that was a good while ago and things have changed. The telephone has been invented, and lots else, and I think we can get it."<ref name="abj" /><ref name="50-369" /> They did have to pay a local building mover and the move took several days, but they were able to install "The Rock" on campus, where it remains a campus landmark.<ref name="abj" /><ref name="50-369" />
Tomlinson graduated from Buchtel in 1880<ref name="abj" /> with a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] and in 1883, with a [[Master of Arts|M.A.]]<ref name="bio">[http://www.zoominfo.com/p/Irving-Tomlinson/167248059 "Rev. Irving C. Tomlinson"] Zoominfo cached from Longyear Museum. Retrieved June 29, 2013</ref> Buchtel later became the municipal [[University of Akron]].<ref name="abj" /> Tomlinson then enrolled in the theological program of [[Tufts College]] in [[Medford, Massachusetts]], receiving a [[Bachelor of Divinity]] degree in 1888.<ref name="bio" /> Soon after graduating, he became the minister at the First Universalist Society of [[Arlington, Massachusetts]], later First Universalist Church.<ref>[http://oasis.lib.harvard.edu/oasis/deliver/~div00572 "First Universalist Society of Arlington, MA. Records, 1841-1965: A Finding Aid"] Andover-Harvard Theological Library, Harvard Divinity School. Retrieved June 29, 2013</ref><ref>[http://cambridge.dlconsulting.com/cgi-bin/cambridge?a=d&d=Tribune18960815-01.2.17 "North Cambridge"] ''The Cambridge Tribune'' (August 15, 1896). Retrieved June 28, 2013</ref>
In 1894, Tomlinson learned of Christian Science and attended his first Christian Science church service and some time later—still a Universalist minister—had [[Christian Science practitioner#Class instruction|primary class instruction]]. Soon after the course was over, however, Tomlinson withdrew from the Universalist church, "[having] found it impossible to ride two horses going in opposite directions."<ref>Tomlinson, Rev. Irving C. ''Twelve Years with Mary Baker Eddy'' (1945), pp. 4-6.</ref> Tomlinson became a member of [[The Mother Church]] in 1897 and in 1898, was invited to be in the last class taught by [[Mary Baker Eddy]].<ref name="csj-bio">[http://journal.christianscience.com/issues/1932/7/50-4/new-member-of-the-christian-science-board-of-lectureship "New Member of The Christian Science Board of Lectureship"] ''Christian Science Journal'' (July 1932). Retrieved June 29, 2013 {{subscription required}}</ref> In 1898, he was also appointed to the Christian Science Board of Lectureship and the following year, he was asked by Eddy to serve as [[Reader (Christian Science Church)|First Reader]] at the church in [[Concord, New Hampshire]];<ref name="csj-bio" /> his sister Mary was asked to serve as Second Reader.<ref>Tomlinson (1945), p. 6</ref> Also in 1898, Eddy asked Tomlinson to serve on the Bible Lesson Committee, which prepares the [[Christian Science Quarterly|lesson-sermons]] read in all Christian Science churches. Tomlinson on this committee at various times until 1927.<ref name="csj-bio" /> In addition, Tomlinson served in other capacities. In 1903 and again in 1921, he was elected president of The Mother Church and most notably, he was one of Eddy's secretaries for 12 years<ref name="scroll" /> and a worker in her household from 1907 to 1910. His book, ''Twelve Years with Mary Baker Eddy'' was published in 1945, the year after his death.<ref>[http://sentinel.christianscience.com/issues/1945/11/47-44/notes-from-the-publishing-society "Notes from the Publishing Society"] ''Christian Science Sentinel'' Volume 47, Issue 44 (November 3, 1945) Retrieved June 30, 2013 {{subscription required}}</ref> In 1928, he taught the [[Normal college|Normal]] class, which trains new teachers of Christian Science and is held just once every three years.<ref name="bio" /><ref name="csj-bio" />
== Published writings (partial list) == * ''The Revelation of Saint John: An Open Book'' (1922) * ''Twelve Years with Mary Baker Eddy'' (1945)
