'''Ittifaq al-Muslimin''' (''The Union of the Muslims''; {{Lang-tt|Иттифак әл-мөслимин}}, ''{{Lang|tt|İttifaq âl-Möslimin}}'', {{Lang-ru|Иттифа́к аль-Муслими́н}})  was a liberal-democratic party of [[Muslims]] in [[Russian Empire]]. The party was formed after ''The First Congress of Muslims of Russia'' and the party line was similar to [[Constitutional Democratic Party|Kadets]]. It was dominated by [[Volga Tatars|Volga Tatar]] intellectuals, but also included [[Azerbaijani people|Azeri]] and [[Crimean Tatars|Crimean Tatar]] representatives.

The main elements of Ittifaq's program were constitutional monarchy, recognition of [[democracy|democratic]] [[Political freedom|freedom]]s, distribution of state available land and [[alpawıt|landowners]]' redeemable land to peasants, equality of [[religion]]s, restitution of [[mosque]]s and [[madrassa]]s belongings to Muslims, etc.

The founders of Ittifaq were Äbüsoğud Äxtämev, [[Yusuf Akçura]], Säyetgäräy Alkin, [[Ismail Gasprinski]], R. İbrahimov, [[Alimardan Topchubashov]], Sälimgäräy Canturin, Äxmäthadi Maqsudi, etc. Permanently worked Central Committee and Central Bureau were elected. Ittifaq played a major part within Muslim fraction of [[State Duma of the Russian Empire]].

