{{Infobox musical artist | name = Rene Rancourt | image = Rene Rancourt (5850995582).jpg | caption = Rancourt participating in the Bruins [[2011 Stanley Cup Finals]] victory parade | background = solo_singer | birth_name = Rene Rancourt | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1939|08|04}} | birth_place = [[Lewiston, Maine]], U.S. | death_date = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date 1st) --> | death_place = | genre = | occupation = [[Singer]] | years_active = <!-- YYYY–YYYY (or –present) --> | label = | associated_acts = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> }} '''Rene Rancourt''' (born August 4, 1939)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunjournal.com/city/story/1040738 |title=Rene Rancourt: Boston Bruins' crooner started here |publisher=Sun Journal |date=2011-06-06 |accessdate=2012-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.publicbackgroundchecks.com/SearchResponse.aspx?view=NM&fn=Rene&mn=&ln=Rancourt&city=&state=&zip=&dob=19390804&age= |title=You searched: Rene Rancourt 19390804 |publisher=Public Background Checks |date= |accessdate=2012-02-28}}</ref> is an American singer. Rancourt has sung the [[The Star-Spangled Banner|U.S.]] and [[O Canada|Canadian]] [[National Anthem|national anthems]] at the [[National Hockey League]]'s [[Boston Bruins]] home [[hockey]] games for over 40 years. He performed his last regular season anthem on April 8, 2018 after 42 years. He sang both anthems before Game 7 of the NHL Eastern Conference quarterfinal playoff series between the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] and Bruins on April 25, 2018.
==Early life== Rancourt was born in [[Lewiston, Maine|Lewiston]], [[Maine]], the son of Leon Rancourt and Bernadette Guenette, French-Canadians from Quebec.<ref>[https://quebec.huffingtonpost.ca/jacques-noel/monsieur-star-spangled-banner-a-boston-est-un-rancourt-damerique_a_23397365/ Monsieur «Star Spangled Banner» à Boston est un Rancourt d'Amérique] Huffington Post</ref><ref>[https://newengland.com/today/living/new-england-nostalgia/rene-rancourt/ Rene Rancourt | Boston’s National Anthem Singer] New England Today</ref><ref>[http://www.salemnews.com/news/state_news/star-spangled-career-bruins-rene-rancourt-reflects-on-a-life/article_0b8ec8bb-9b87-50db-abe7-5b5e4eb46192.html Star-spangled career: Bruins' Rene Rancourt reflects on a life defined by the national anthem] The Salem News</ref>
==Career== Rancourt first began singing the anthem in Boston at [[Fenway Park]]. He took part in an [[opera]] singing audition on the [[radio]] and was heard by [[John Kiley]], long-time [[organist]] at both Fenway and the Boston Garden. Rancourt sang before Game 6 of the [[1975 World Series|World Series]] in 1975 when singer [[Kate Smith]] cancelled her appearance. Rancourt's ambition was to become an opera singer. The strength of his trained voice overcame the acoustic shortcomings of the old [[Boston Garden]].<ref>http://warwickonline.com/stories/bruins-anthem-singer-coming-to-reds-reunion-this-weekend,38806?print=1</ref> In 1976, he began singing regularly for [[Boston Bruins]] games.
Rancourt's signature fist-pump at the end of the anthem was modeled after the "Stump Pump" of former Bruin [[Randy Burridge]], whom Rancourt admired. Rancourt also salutes at the end of the anthem. The salute is for men and women who have served in the armed forces, although it was initially inspired by an elderly fan of Rancourt.<ref>https://sports.vice.com/en_us/article/legendary-boston-bruins-anthem-singer-rene-rancourt-reflects-on-his-career?curator=SportsREDEF</ref> Rancourt performs the anthem before Bruins games, as well as singing at auto races, charity events and nursing homes in and around New England. He does not have a contract with the Bruins. According to Rancourt, "I've never had a contract; I've always just shown up and I've become associated with the Bruins."
Rancourt served in the U.S. Army in the 1960s in which after winning a singing contest he was assigned to GI traveling show which kept him from being sent to [[Vietnam War|Vietnam]].<ref>[http://www.sunjournal.com/city/story/1040738 "Rene Rancourt: Bruins crooner got his start here" Lewiston-Auburn (ME) Sun Journal, June 6, 2011]</ref>
On January 17, 2018, the Bruins announced that Rancourt would retire at the end of the [[2017–18 NHL season|2017–18 season]]. He was honored during the Bruins' last regular season game against the [[Florida Panthers]] on April 8.<ref>{{cite web|last1=bostonbruins.com|title=Bruins Announce Rene Rancourt's Retirement|url=https://www.nhl.com/bruins/news/bruins-announce-rene-rancourts-retirement/c-295026710|website=NHL.com|accessdate=January 17, 2018}}</ref> His final playoff game was Game 4 of the Eastern Conference Second Round vs. the [[Tampa Bay Lightning]] on May 4, 2018. After the Lightning eliminated the Bruins in five games, he retired for good.
